explanation: OS_CHECK_POINTER — macro/func may abort, return, or otherwise alter control flow early; needed to know whether subsequent code can be reached. OS_CHECK_SIZE — same as above for size checks; may make later code unreachable. OS_ObjectIdGetById — its return semantics determine whether the if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) branch is reachable. OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET — macro expands to access of the object table; needed to see if it can cause early exit, assertions, or produce a valid queue pointer. OS_queue_table — the object table symbol used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; needed to know table contents/valid indices and whether lookup can fail or assert. OS_queue_internal_record_t — type definition (contains max_size); required to determine whether reading queue->max_size is valid and whether that access can cause undefined behavior or be elided. OS_QueuePut_Impl — callee of the reachable branch; needed to know whether the call can be inlined/optimized away or otherwise affect reachability analysis. OS_SUCCESS — value compared against return_code; must know its value/domain semantics. OS_QUEUE_INVALID_SIZE — returned in the size-check branch; needed to confirm the branch is a real return path. OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE — argument to OS_ObjectIdGetById that may affect its behavior/return; needed to determine possible outcomes. LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE — same as above (affects lookup result). OS_object_token_t — token type used by ObjectIdGetById and OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its layout/valid values can affect whether lookup and subsequent table access are valid. osal_id_t — type of queue_id parameter; needed to know whether certain id values are impossible/filtered earlier. int32, size_t, uint32 — basic types used by function signature and variables; included so an analyzer can reason about ranges/overflows and whether any checks/macros depend on exact types. Together, these symbols define the control-flow and data accesses in OS_QueuePut; their definitions are required to determine if any branch or statement in the function is provably unreachable (MISRA unreachable-code analysis).
